<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/18308825-david-peterson"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1363134675i/18308825.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/18308825-david-peterson">David Peterson</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">As mentioned below, there is a glossary to help, and even a wiki (google anathem wiki) if you don&apos;t mind some spoilers. That said, the way this one wa<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">As mentioned below, there is a glossary to help, and even a wiki (google anathem wiki) if you don't mind some spoilers. That said, the way this one was written, I'd recommend starting over - this may be the first book I've ever done this with, but when I finished I went right back and re-read it to pick up things that I'd missed the significance of on the first read. Coming at those first couple hundred pages with fresh eyes, and the spoilers of the future makes them even better.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
