<div id="review_2447083171" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2447083171" />
    <a title="Eye of Sauron" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/61597976-eye-of-sauron"><img alt="Eye of Sauron" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479408483p2/61597976.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2447083171?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eye of Sauron" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eye of Sauron" href="/user/show/61597976-eye-of-sauron">Eye of Sauron</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Eye of Sauron by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/4213258-bradley">Bradley</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=five-star-novels">five-star-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=top-25-novels">top-25-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=top-100-novels">top-100-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61597976-eye-of-sauron?shelf=all-time-favorites">all-time-favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2447083171" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1336226225000349880">WOW.<br/><br/>Farewell, YA Fantasy; I don&apos;t believe I&apos;m ever coming back.<br/><br/><b>This is one fantastic book.</b> Stephenson combines philosophy, mystery, science fiction, fantasy, anthropology, satire, and a lot more in what is probably one of my new favorite books of all time. Certainly the best novel I&apos;ve read that was written post-2000. <br/><br/><i>Anathem</i>&apos;s worldbuilding (physical, cultural, historical, philosophical, etc.) is brilliant. The <i>concent of the avout</i> idea is pretty much my idea of a utopia: it&apos;s a massive, comple</span>
  <span id="freeText1336226225000349880" style="display:none">WOW.<br /><br />Farewell, YA Fantasy; I don't believe I'm ever coming back.<br /><br /><b>This is one fantastic book.</b> Stephenson combines philosophy, mystery, science fiction, fantasy, anthropology, satire, and a lot more in what is probably one of my new favorite books of all time. Certainly the best novel I've read that was written post-2000. <br /><br /><i>Anathem</i>'s worldbuilding (physical, cultural, historical, philosophical, etc.) is brilliant. The <i>concent of the avout</i> idea is pretty much my idea of a utopia: it's a massive, complex societal structure whose members' primary function is <b>philosophizing</b>. They have no currency and few personal possessions, and basically embody what would happen if Plato's Academy grew to eat the world. They regularly and casually engage in Dialog, which is a logical and rhetorical debate in which the participants take nothing for granted and attempt to find truth while "planing" each other. I LOVE IT.<br /><br />Stephenson clearly took many of his ideas from Western philosophical tradition, with lots of little nods to Plato, Aristotle, Einstein, Jules Verne, and many others. The avout even have their own slightly different version of Occam's Razor, which they call the Steelyard. Much of the book consists of these formal Dialogs, but they are <b>absolutely fascinating</b>. What is consciousness? Why do we worry? How valid is the multiverse theory? Does time exist? Do we exist? (All of these are important to the plot, by the way, not just random rabbit trails.)<br /><br />I'm not doing this justice. If it sounds at all interesting to you, you should absolutely read it. Although it is 900+ pages long, it's worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1336226225000349880" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


